---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a sunken or lifted segmental driveway be repaired without ripping it all out?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Often yes — if the pavers themselves are still in good shape and the failure is localised (a 1-3m² area that's sunk or lifted), we can lift the affected pavers, regrade the base, re-bed and polymeric-sand the joint zone. Full re-lay costs ~$60-$140/m² depending on whether we need to remove and replace base or just re-screed bedding. Compare that to $130-$200/m² for a full new segmental driveway. If the problem is widespread (over 30% of the area sunken, or multiple failure zones), full lift-and-relay of the whole area is usually more economical because the labour mobilisation per m² drops. We assess at the site visit and give honest advice — sometimes the right answer is to repair localised areas and let the rest run, sometimes a full re-lay is genuinely the cheaper outcome." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do segmental pavers sink — and what's the actual fix?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Three common causes: (1) bedding sand washed out through joints (no polymeric sand) — the sand under the paver finds its way out through the joint, paver sinks; (2) base inadequately compacted at install — base settles unevenly, paver follows; (3) localised excavation under the paving (utility trench, root growth, animal burrow) — voids cause local sinking. The fix differs by cause. Cause 1: lift area, sweep out washed-bedding-sand gaps, fresh screened bedding sand, re-lay pavers, polymeric-sand all joints (including adjacent intact ones) to stop recurrence. Cause 2 + 3: lift area, excavate to expose problem, re-compact or fill void, fresh base, fresh bedding, re-lay. Always: identify the cause first, otherwise the repair just moves the failure 1m sideways." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you extend my existing paved driveway to match?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, with two caveats. First: paver matching. Adbri, Boral and Brikmakers segmental pavers all have batch-to-batch colour variation, and discontinued styles can be impossible to source. We bring you 3-5 colour-matched options and you choose what's closest. The new section will be a deliberate visual band (separated by an edge or change of pattern) rather than a seamless extension — trying to seamlessly blend old to new usually looks worse than honest blocking. Second: levels and falls. The new section needs to tie into the existing levels at a defined point and carry the existing falls; we re-screed the join zone to make this work. Typical extension cost: $130-$200/m² for the new area, $60-$100/m to dress the join zone." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I just replace the bedding sand under existing pavers as routine maintenance?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Not usually — bedding sand replacement is invasive (every paver in the area needs lifting) and the right call only if a real problem exists. Joint sand top-up IS routine maintenance: pavers laid 10 years ago with white silica sand will have lost most of it; sweeping fresh polymeric sand into joints stops further problems for another 10-15 years. Cost: ~$8-$15/m² for joint sand refresh, includes sweep, water-mist activate, set. If you've also got minor settlement, the polymeric joint refresh sometimes locks the remaining bedding in place and stops further movement. We're happy to assess existing paving and recommend the lowest-cost option that actually solves the issue." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long does a segmental paving repair take?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Small localised repair (1-3m² lift-and-relay): 1 day on-site, plus 1-2 days for polymeric sand to cure before traffic. Joint sand refresh on an existing driveway: 1 day on-site, drive on after 24-48 hours depending on rain. Extension of existing paving (10-15m²): 2-4 working days. Larger re-lay over base prep work (20-40m²): 4-7 days. We schedule short jobs Tuesday-Thursday so weather curing is best, and always polymeric-sand on a forecast dry day — wet activation is fine, but rain before initial set washes joint sand back out." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What if the original pavers are discontinued — can I still get matched repair?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Sometimes — paver yards (Australian Paving Centre, Local Mowers & Stone, builders' demolition yards) often have small leftover stock of discontinued lines and that's the first place we check. For larger jobs where matching stock isn't available: option A is salvage existing pavers from a sacrificial area (e.g. lift pavers from a hidden side-path to use for the visible repair, then re-lay the hidden area with a different but acceptable paver); option B is honest blocking — repair zone with a complementary contrast paver, deliberately framed by an edge course of the original. Both look intentional rather than failed. Worth a 5-min phone call with photos of your existing paver — we can usually tell you in advance whether match-stock is realistic." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Segmental Paving Repair Officer | Re-lay, Extend, Restore | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Segmental paving repair, re-lay and extension for Officer, Cardinia Lakes, Beaconsfield, Pakenham — fix sunken or lifted pavers, polymeric-sand existing joints, extend driveways to match. Cheaper than full replacement."
  canonical="https://officerpavingco.com.au/services/segmental-paving/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Repair, re-lay, extend</span>
      <h1>Segmental paving repair in <span class="accent">Officer &amp; Cardinia Shire</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Lift sunken or heaved pavers, regrade the base, re-bed, re-lay and polymeric-sand
        the joints. Extend an existing driveway. Refresh joints on a 10-year-old
        patio. Honest, cheaper-than-replacement work for pavers that still have life
        left in them.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>When segmental repair is the right call.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>Good candidates for repair.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Sunken or lifted patch under 30% of the total paved area</li>
          <li>Pavers themselves still in good condition &mdash; minimal chipping, colour OK</li>
          <li>Base appears sound elsewhere &mdash; the failure is localised, not systemic</li>
          <li>10&ndash;25 year old driveways or patios that lost their joint sand (washed out by rain over years)</li>
          <li>Driveway extension when adding a carport, widening a single to a double, or extending around a new pool / addition</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Bad candidates (need full replacement).</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Over 50% of paved area sunken / heaved / cracked &mdash; systemic base failure</li>
          <li>Pavers themselves heavily chipped, salt-bleached or structurally damaged</li>
          <li>Tree roots growing under and lifting wide areas (root removal + base rebuild is more invasive than fresh paving)</li>
          <li>Underlying drainage failure (water actively coming up through pavers) &mdash; needs full base-and-drainage rebuild</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Our repair process.</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Inspection (free):</strong> Walk the paving, lift a representative paver to inspect bedding and base, identify the failure cause. Without identifying cause, the repair just relocates the failure 1m sideways.</li>
          <li><strong>Lift:</strong> Carefully remove affected pavers, preserving each one (we&rsquo;ll need them back, unless we&rsquo;re replacing with matched stock). Lay out in correct re-install order.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-prep base:</strong> Excavate any settled or washed-out sub-base, re-compact existing Class 3 base or top up where needed, re-screed bedding sand to correct level.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-lay:</strong> Pavers re-laid in original pattern, cuts re-fitted at edges, levels checked against adjacent unaffected paving.</li>
          <li><strong>Polymeric sand:</strong> All joints in repair area + at least 500mm into surrounding unaffected paving swept with polymeric sand, mist-activated, cured. This stops recurrence at the repair boundary.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why your joints washed out (and the polymeric-sand fix).</h3>
        <p>
          Most segmental paving laid in Officer before about 2018 used white
          silica jointing sand. It looked good day one but washed out within
          2&ndash;5 winters &mdash; the open joints then let bedding sand escape,
          water find its way under pavers, and ants colonise. The result: settled
          patches, lifted edges, weeds. The fix is polymeric sand &mdash;
          $8&ndash;$15/m&sup2; for a full driveway joint refresh, ~$80&ndash;$120
          per 22kg bag covering ~12m&sup2;. Sweep into joints, mist-wet, polymer
          activates and sets to a flexible-rigid water-shedding joint. We do
          joint refresh on its own as a 1-day job and it adds 10&ndash;15 years
          to the life of the existing paving.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Extending existing paving &mdash; the two challenges.</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Paver matching:</strong> Adbri, Boral and Brikmakers segmental
          pavers all have batch-to-batch colour variation, and many older
          patterns are discontinued. We bring 3&ndash;5 colour-matched options
          to your site visit; you pick the closest. The new section is usually
          presented as a deliberate band (separated by an edge course or change
          of pattern) rather than a seamless extension &mdash; honest blocking
          looks better than failed blending.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Levels and falls:</strong> The new section ties into existing
          levels at a defined point and carries existing falls. We re-screed the
          join zone, install an expansion / edge restraint at the boundary, and
          confirm drainage works across the whole area before paver-lay.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical repair pricing (Cardinia Shire 2026).</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Small spot repair (1&ndash;3m&sup2; lift-and-relay): $400&ndash;$900 minimum job</li>
          <li>Localised re-lay 5&ndash;10m&sup2;: $700&ndash;$1,500</li>
          <li>Joint sand refresh on existing 60m&sup2; driveway: $500&ndash;$900</li>
          <li>Driveway extension 10&ndash;15m&sup2; matched: $1,800&ndash;$3,200</li>
          <li>Full re-lay 30&ndash;50m&sup2; over fresh base: $4,500&ndash;$8,500</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">When discontinued pavers stop a match.</h3>
        <p>
          Sometimes the original pavers aren&rsquo;t available. Option A:
          salvage from a hidden side-path to use for the visible repair, then
          re-lay the hidden area with a different acceptable paver. Option B:
          honest blocking &mdash; repair zone in a complementary contrast paver,
          framed by an edge course of original. Both read as intentional, not
          failed. Worth a 5-min phone call with photos of your existing paver
          &mdash; we can usually tell you on the spot whether match-stock is
          realistic.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Where we work.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/officer/">Officer</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-lakes/">Cardinia Lakes</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/beaconsfield/">Beaconsfield</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/pakenham/">Pakenham</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/heritage-springs/">Heritage Springs</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-shire/">All Cardinia Shire</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Free segmental paving assessment.</h2>
        <p>Honest repair-vs-replace call. Fixed quote within 48 hours.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Quote online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
